shared_text:
Mrs Speechie P
June 19 at 6:15 PM ·

I will say this over and over! Are there flash cards, apps, and toys that can help kids learn? Absolutely! But- kids will learn SO MUCH MORE when they are engaging with others during those activities - and when it comes to language, I really believe they can learn even more through good old fashioned play with another person- regardless of what toys or objects are involved!

post_text: Dolly Parton's Imagination Library has come to USD 415!! Any family with children up to age 5 can register and receive a free book every month!
shared_text:
Hiawatha Public Schools-USD 415
May 8 at 12:54 PM ·

Any family with a child(ren) under the age of 5 (up to 58 month) living in USD 415 Hiawatha Schools is now available to receive FREE once a month books mailed directly to their home. Families can build a home library and increase opportunities for language and literacy building. Register your child by going to www.imaginationlibrary.com and clicking on “register my child” You will be prompted to enter your place of residence. Greenbush is acting as an administrator for this project which is being funded by the LINK consortium. If you have any questions regarding registering a child, please contact: Gena Allen (gena.allen@greenbush.org) or by calling 1-800-554-3412

shared_text:
Mommy & Me Milestones
March 19 at 7:49 AM ·

#singanddance and #read
•
Work in progress!... Adjusting to a new schedule that involves life at home with your kids and finding the right balance will take time. Good days and bad days will be had. •
Maybe you and your child thrive on keeping a set schedule with lesson plans or maybe you feel like you are just surviving! The most important thing is figuring out what works for you and your child(ren).
•
We are trying to find balance by incorporating a variety of activies each day that allow us to create, connect, move, work, sing, dance, read, and PLAY! I loosely plan a few structured activities around these categories for each day. This is helping us, mostly ME, because *I just can't* "play cars" and "talk like cars" all day and maintain my sanity! 🙃
•
#daysathome #stayhome #toddlerlockdown #sendhelp #homebound #toddlermom #boymom #slpmom #slpbloggers #learnathome #slpeeps #slpsofinstagram

shared_text:
Mommy & Me Milestones
February 11 at 1:50 PM ·

Giving choices! 📚
✔️Encourages spontaneous word use
✔️ Models and reinforces vocabulary
✔️ Teaches reciprocal communication
•
The many benefits of using choices throughout your daily routines! Did I mention that choices can also help avoid power struggles and give your child the illusion of being in control? 😉🤣 If your child is saying a few words, they are ready for choices. Hold up an item in each hand and show them the choices as you say them. "Do you want the apple (hold out apple) or the banana (hold out banana)?"
•
The video for teaching this skill should be available later this week!
•
#expressivelanguage
#languagedevelopment
#choices #earlyintervention
#eislp #speechtherapy
#speechpathology #speechie #slpmom #toddlermom #toddlerlife #slplife #slpeeps #slp2b

post_text: What a simple and great idea!
shared_text:
Mommy & Me Milestones
January 14 at 10:21 AM ·

Replace "IF" and "WHEN" with "FIRST, THEN"!
•
Your toddler is still learning language, so keep it simple to help them be more successful.
•
❎If you don't wash your hands, you can't have snack.
❎We can eat snack when you wash your hands.
✔️ FIRST wash hands, THEN eat snack.
•
This is a great strategy for teaching follow through on a less desirable task prior to doing a highly preferred task.
•
Here are some that I use daily:
First put on shoes, Then go outside.
First, wash hands, Then eat snack.
First brush teeth, Then read books.
•
#followingdirections #toddlermilestones #firstthen #speechtherapy #speechpathology #earlyintervention #eislp #slpmom #toddlermom #firsttimemom #parentingtips #toddlerhood #slpeeps #slp2b
#slpsofinstagram

The Kansas Health Foundation statewide campaign elevates awareness of the reading gap and encourages parents to read with their children. Research shows that two out of every five kids begin kindergarten unprepared. Don't let your child be one of them!

shared_text:
Mommy & Me Milestones
October 29, 2019 at 11:46 AM ·

Mama, ball, dada, up, hi, wawa (water) no, hat... There is a reason these words are at the top of the list for first words! They contain sounds that are easier for your child to say 🙌
Your child will also be more successful with words if they already babble those sounds. So listen to the sounds your child is already saying and use those to build first words!

shared_text:
Babble Talk Read - BTR
October 3, 2019 at 6:00 PM ·

Ninety percent of a child’s brain growth occurs during birth and 4 years of age, which is why it's so important to read to your child from the time they are babies.

Reading will also help create a bond between you and your child, so find opportunities to read every day. You don't need much preparation. Setting aside 5-10 minutes each day will be enough to make a big difference in your child's life!

#btrprogram #babbletalkread #readingtime #parenthood

shared_text:
Babble Talk Read - BTR
August 27, 2019 at 8:00 PM ·

For 4 and 5-year-old children, the understanding of books goes much deeper. A good strategy to keep in mind is to ask them to talk about any topic they would like to. Listen to what they have to say and follow up with questions. Ask too for them to describe details.

Remember to point out pictures after reading the text, as children often use the content within pictures to respond to questions, instead of words. Provide clear, simple visuals to support vocabulary learning.
#btrprogram #babbletalkread #readingtime

August 19, 2019 at 8:00 PM ·

Parents of 2-year-olds should read to young children one-on-one, in an engaging manner, pointing to pictures. Keep book sharing positive.

Remember that learning doesn't have to be structured, but it should be enjoyable. There is no ""right"" way to read a book!

shared_text:
Babble Talk Read - BTR
August 14, 2019 at 8:01 PM ·

There are individual differences in how children engage with books, but 1-year-olds tend to be more responsive, particularly if they have been read to since they were infants and have had positive experiences with books.

A pattern of daily reading over time is related to language and cognitive development. Make it a habit to dedicate part of the day to something related to books; either read them or simply play with them. Anything counts!

#btrprogram #babbletalkread #earlyliteracy

August 9, 2019 at 8:00 PM ·

From 6-12 months, babies are excited to explore everything. When it comes to developing their reading skills, it's important to repeat actions such as reading the same book over and over, using the same emphasis each time as you would with a familiar song.

Encourage infants to touch the book or hold cloth and other materials.

shared_text:
Babble Talk Read - BTR
August 8, 2019 at 8:01 PM ·

Sometimes it's challenging to know exactly what your child should be doing at any given age.

For newborns, is important you cuddle with them while you read so they feel safe, warm, and connected to you.

Sing nursery rhymes, make funny animal sounds, or bounce older toddlers on your knee. Show that reading is fun and make sure to use different expressions.

#btrprogram #babbletalkread #parenthood #earlyliteracy
